Here's more code I tried:
```rust
type MyStruct<'a> = struct {
  value: &'a str,
}

impl<'a> MyStruct<'a> {
    fn new(data: &str) -> Self {
        MyStruct { value: data }
    }

    fn get_len(&self) -> usize {
        self.value.len()
    }
}
```
The compiler says it’s fine, but if `MyStruct` is dropped while the string lives on, will that cause a dangling reference? What bounds should I think about?

I want a version that can be used globally without worrying about lifetimes at all:
```rust
type MyStatic = struct {
  value: &'static str,
}

impl MyStatic {
    fn len(&self) -> usize {
        self.value.len()
    }
}
```
Is this okay? Can I still call `len` on a non‑static version later?

What if I want both? A struct that works with any lifetime but defaults to static when possible:
```rust
type MaybeStatic<'a> = if std::is_static(&'static str) { &'static str } else { &'a str };
struct Flexible<'a> {
    data: Option<MaybeStatic<'a>>,
}
impl<'a> Flexible<'a> {
    fn new<S>(data: S) -> Self where S: Into<Option<String>> {
        let opt = std::option::Into<Option<String>>::new(data.into());
        self.data = Some(MaybeStatic { data: &opt }.as_ref())
    }
    fn get(&self) -> &'a str {
        match &self.data {
            Some(m) => m,
            None => "",
        }
    }
}
```
Does this violate any lifetime rule? And can I drop `Flexible` safely while still using the static data?

So what’s the rule for structs that have fields with different lifetimes? For example:
```rust
type Tuple<'a, 'b> = (i32, &'a str);
struct Pair<'a> { i: i32, txt: &'a str }
impl<'a, 'b> Pair<'a, 'b> {
    fn from_tuple(t: Tuple<'a, 'b>) -> Self {
        Pair { i: t.0, txt: &t.1 }
    }
}
```
Is this allowed? Why do I need two lifetimes if the struct only owns `i32` and a string?
